Languages, as an option, are now seen in the same way as STEM themes (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and not only.
A UK Employment and Competition Commission survey in 2014 concluded that, among the reasons for the difficulties of employers in filling vacancies, 17% were concerned with the shortage of language skills.
Therefore, learning other languages is increasingly an imperative to prepare the young generation for their future careers.
With more potential employment opportunities to demand language knowledge, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career chosen, if they have learned a second language, they will have a tangible advantage in the future with an aptitude for life like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically place a multilingual person in front of competition.
According to a survey of YouGov more than 4000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to maintain a conversation, the French being the only language spoken by a two-digit ratio, 15%.
So investing now in language teaching is important for children today.
The domain of several languages, particularly those of developing countries, will give children the best chance of finding employment with relevance.
In Scotland, each school differs in the languages it teaches.
Some of them will focus on the most classic modern languages, while others will teach languages considered the most important for the UK for the 2020 horizon, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be a set of languages to choose from in independent schools, supported by specialized teachers in the area.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a pedagogical environment that prepares children and gives them the skills necessary for success, whatever future reserves them.
It is undeniable that today, in a globalised business environment, languages continue to be of fundamental importance for the future of the country, so it is necessary to reflect it in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to make this option available with diversity and excellence for young Scottish people.
We have to do this.
