Updated information about the Red Sea: Decreased concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to new information from Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission, there was a decrease in Red Sea concentrations in some areas of Tampa Bay.
FWC reported that conditions of lower proliferation of stains were identified in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a decrease in concentrations.
The Red Sea stain extends about 201 km along the coast, from Pinellas County to the north to Lee County to the south.
Spots can be found about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in less areas than last week.
The Red Sea was also seen in Pasco County.
Last week, average concentrations were recorded along or off the coast of Pinella County, low to high off the coast of Hillsborough County, low to high concentrations in Manatee County, high to high to or off the coast of Sarasota County, medium to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, high to high down to or off the coast of Lee County County, and low to high concentrations in Collier County.
There are still reports of respiratory irritation in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
In the last week, there were no reports of respiratory irritations in the northwestern Florida region.
